{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1460161509,"nonce":"2m77K+86wys4HWPlh6FxByc8VnI=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDIwNzY2MTQ2Mw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/716#issuecomment-207661463"},"message":"\u003e @bgruening First off, I want to say that I completely understand the value of the `depot` in terms of practicality and making things \"just work\". For that reason, I think it's likely worth the tradeoffs. However, I do think there are tradeoffs in complexity (it's at least a mirror and point of failure), and in transparency.\n\nShouldn't be if documented well, here we failed obviously.\n\n\u003e 1. When I look at a tool in the toolshed, I see that it's downloading some tarball from `depot`. I can't (easily) determine what that code is, where it came from, how it was generated, etc. In this instance, I had no way of knowing it was an unmodified tarball from bioconductor. (Is that even correct?)\n\nYes, this is correct. You find this information in the depot github site. It's all contained in a tsv file.\nWe wanted to make this more transparent and here is a little bit of history and an outline what we wanted to do:\n\nhttps://gist.github.com/bgruening/48297c27cd72cbadea7a\n\n\u003e 1. In addition to not really know what the code is, I have no simple way to contribute updates or fixes to it. This is a piece that is potentially separate from either the tool in the toolshed or the upstream tool itself. BTW, in this case, I think I'd have a preference to keep the Galaxy specific code in the Galaxy toolshed repository and not a separate (third) repo.\n\nMh this one I does not understand. You can just add a newline to the cargo-port tsv file and can store a new tarball. Changing tarballs is not the purpose of cargo-port. This is a really stupid store. It just mirrors source. It really only solves the problem that many tarballs just disappear over time.\n\n\u003e 1. My Galaxy installation is now dependent on the `depot` being up and maintained by the Galaxy team. While this is a nice service, it's an added level of dependency that wasn't there when the recipes simply got the source code directly from the upstream project.\n\nIn the gist we explained how we want to first look at the original source of the source and only in case of a 404 look at depot. Moreover, I trust depot more than some random other FTP server, but this might be just me :) \n\n\u003e I do believe that documentation could go a long way to mitigating these issues. Perhaps adding information to the wiki as well as a landing page on https://depot.galaxyproject.org/ that helps people to understand what is there and how it was generated.\n\nI'm willing to write something about this and maybe you can improve it until it is understandable :)\nI'm just not sure if this worth the effort, actually all this will not be needed in a few month if everything goes well and we are using conda (and Docker) packages for everything.\n\n\u003e In short, I very much appreciate everyone's efforts and I do think things are getting more reliable, but from my perspective they are getting increasingly complex and the documentation of how things work, how things are changing, and where things are going is lacking. For example, conda, docker, depot, and starforge are all things I've heard of, but don't fully grasp how the Galaxy Project is using them.\n\nSorry for that. I'm aware of the increased complexity of all these new technologies, it's a rough time as we are in a transition phase. I'm happy to document all this or give an outline of how imagine things will work in a few month. If everything goes well all what we need to care about is a conda package and the rest we will get for free as `depot` and docker will be integrated upstream - into the various conda repositories.\n\n@lparsons happy to chat with you about that, maybe you can help me to write this down.","files":null}]}